, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"North","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>north</i> ‘north’, denoting someone who had migrated from the north, especially someone from northern England living in the south of the country. It may also have been used to denote someone living in the northern part of a settlement or region.","Irish: in Ireland, adopted for <b>Mac an Ultaigh</b> ‘son of the Ulsterman’, Ulster being the northern part of Ireland.","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name composed with a cognate of Old High German <i>nord</i> ‘north’."],"variants":[{"name":"McNulty","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aidan, Brennan, Brigid, Dermot, Dympna, Kieran, Michael Patrick, Niall.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Ultaigh</b> ‘son of the Ulsterman’. This is the name of a Donegal family originally from County Down. It has sometimes been Anglicized as   North  ."]},{"name":"Nortz","meanings":["North German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name (see   North   3).","South German: perhaps a metonymic occupational name for someone who trapped otters or for someone who dealt in otter skins, from Middle High German <i>nörz</i> ‘otter’."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ellen North was born about 1420, in Walkeringham, Nottinghamshire, England. She had at least 1 son with John Ringwood Killigrew. She died in 0001, in England."},"et":{"about 1420–1480":"umbes 1420–0001","1420–1461":"1420–1461","1445–1501":"1445–1501","1420–0001":"1420–0001","1501":"1501","1445":"1445","1420":"1420","0001":"0001","1461":"1461","about 1420":"umbes 1420","1480":"0001","Walkeringham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Walkeringham, Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1420–1480":"noin 1420–0001","1420–1461":"1420–1461","1445–1501":"1445–1501","1420–0001":"1420–0001","1501":"1501","1445":"1445","1420":"1420","0001":"0001","1461":"1461","about 1420":"noin 1420","1480":"0001","Walkeringham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Walkeringham, Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1420–1480":"environ 1420–0001","1420–1461":"1420–1461","1445–1501":"1445–1501","1420–0001":"1420–0001","1501":"1501","1445":"1445","1420":"1420","0001":"0001","1461":"1461","about 1420":"environ 1420","1480":"0001","Walkeringham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Walkeringham, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Ellen North est née environ 1420, à Walkeringham, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec John Ringwood Killigrew. Elle est décédée en 0001, à Angleterre."},"de":{"about 1420–1480":"um 1420–0001","1420–1461":"1420–1461","1445–1501":"1445–1501","1420–0001":"1420–0001","1501":"1501","1445":"1445","1420":"1420","0001":"0001","1461":"1461","about 1420":"um 1420","1480":"0001","Walkeringham, Nott